Chilean Sea Bass

A Chilean sea bass recipe that will knock your socks off. This turns out so yummy and delicious every time. Pair it with your favorite sides and enjoy! Let us know what you think!

Jump To Recipe

What is Chilean Sea Bass?

Chilean Sea Bass aren't even a bass. What's up with that. They are actually a Patagonian toothfish. They are large, and they we originally caught by Chilean longline fishermen along the continental shelf. They are typically found down around 5,000 to 6,000 feet.

What does chilean Sea Bass Taste like?

They are a rich fish that melts in your mouth. Add butter to the plate and you are going to be in heaven. This is an absolutely delicious and beautiful looking fish.  The fish meat is incredibly tender and moist. When you cut it, it breaks into large, thick flakey pieces. It has been described as oily compared to other fish, which is why it has such a rich flavor. When cooked the fish stays just as white as when you bought it. In appearance a fish that is similar to Chilean sea bass is cod.

Is Chilean sea bass fattening?

Much of the flavor that Chilean Sea Bass contains is due to its high levels of Omega-3 Fatty acids. This aspect of the fish makes it not only delicious, but makes it very beneficial to your health. The first of the benefits of Omega-3 fatty acid is how it helps keep your eyes healthy.

Calories in chilean sea bass cooked

Bass, Chilean Sea

Calories: 184
Fat Calories: 130
Total Fat: 14.2 g
Saturated Fat: 3.2 g
Cholesterol: 49 mg

Chilean Sea Bass Calories

184

Bass, Chilean Sea

Calories: 184
Total Fat: 14.2 g
Saturated Fat: 3.2 g
Cholesterol: 49 mg
Sodium: 56 mg

What temperature is Chilean sea bass?

145 degrees F.

What temperature to cook Chilean sea bass? No matter how you cook it, you want to make sure that the internal temperature of all fish and seafood reaches 145 degrees F.

What goes well with Chilean sea bass?

Something simple like a buttery rice, and orzo pilaf, or roasted fingerling potatoes. Let the sea bass be the star.

Chilean Sea Bass

Dietary
Oil Free
Sugar Free
Low Carb
Calories per serving
105
Servings
1
Ingredients
  • 3.5 oz sea bass fillets
  • 2 cloves garlic, minced
  • 1/2 lemon
  • 1/2 t pink salt
  • 1/2 t lemon pepper
  • 2 T chopped cilantro (optional)
  • 1/2 t paprika
Directions
  1. Preheat oven to 450 degrees
  2. Arrange sea bass fillets in a single layer on foil-lined broiler pan
  3. Spread garlic and cilantro on and around fish
  4. Squeeze lemon juice on fillets, sprinkle salt and lemon pepper to taste, and add paprika for color
  5. Cover with foil and crimp edges to form a seal
  6. Bake for 20 minutes

Crustless Apple Pie Cups

These are so cute for parties. What's more, is that these are a really healthy treat and no one will even suspect it. Try them today and let us know how they came out.

Crustless Apple Pie Cups

Dietary
Oil Free
Sugar Free
Low Carb
Calories per serving
40
Servings
6
Ingredients
  • 1 egg 
  • 1/2 c. egg whites
  • 1/2 c. unsweetened applesauce
  • 12 drops vanilla or english toffee stevia
  • 1/2 small apple, cored and finely chopped
  • 1 tsp. cinnamon
Directions
  1. Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
  2. Place egg, egg whites, applesauce, and stevia in blender and pulse until combined.
  3. Pour mixture evenly into 6 silicone muffin tins.
  4. In small bowl, mix stir cinnamon into chopped apples until well coated.
  5. Spoon apple pieces evenly into each muffin tin.
  6. Bake for 30 mins.
  7. Remove from oven and allow to come to room temperature then refrigerate for 20 minutes.

Tuna Salad on Cucumber Crackers

This is such a simple and fast recipe. You can really make this one your own too. Try different combos and dressings in the tuna salad or make it as simple as you want. 

Tuna Salad on Cucumber Crackers

Dietary
Oil Free
Sugar Free
Low Carb
Calories per serving
180
Servings
1
Ingredients
  • 1 (4oz) can Albacore Tuna in water
  • 8 oz cucumber, sliced
  • 1 T dijon mustard
  • 1/2 t apple cider vinegar
  • stevia, to taste
  • salt and pepper, to taste
Directions
  1. Combine tuna, mustard, acv, stevia, salt and pepper in a bowl
  2. Place a spoonful of tuna salad on each cucumber slice

90 Second Almond Bread

If you are on a keto diet or a grain free diet then this 90 second bread will be right up your ally. There are also a lot of health benefits to using almond flour... try this recipe out and let us know how you like it. It'll only take you 90 seconds. :)

 

Jump To Recipe

Almond flour is a great low carb flour to use as a substitute when making homemade bread.

I began using almond flour right after switching to a grain-free diet because it was all that was around at that point. I quickly found that my baked goods seemed to be too moist and greasy, so I started introducing just a bit of coconut flour into my recipes to help absorb some of the moisture. The combination of the two seemed to work well, and I stuck exclusively to those for a while. I noticed though, that eating too many baked goods with almond flour too often caused my stomach to act up, so I limit the amount of treats I eat, and also now like to use other grain-free flours like cashew and sunflower seed flour to change things up a bit. I also recently started experimenting with arrowroot powder, green banana flour too.

Tips for the perfect 90 second bread

The finer the almond flour is ground, the better your baked goods will turn out. If you use a courser ground flour, your product will be much more grainy and the texture will be as if you added nuts to the batter. 90 second bread doesn't have to be grainy so take your time and grind it longer.

Be careful, nut flours can burn easily. That is why this recipe calls for a lower baking temperature and longer time than you would use with a normal flour recipe. Since all ovens heat differently be sure to watch your oven temp and check your bake times.

Almond flour can get expensive, but you can get a discount if you buy in bulk. You can store almond flour in your refrigerator for about a month and in your freezer for around 6-8 months. If you store it in your freezer, just remove the portion of this low carb flour that you need for your recipe and let thaw at room temperature for around 25-30 minutes.

Almond Meal is different than Almond Flour. Almond Meal is ground almonds with the skin on, while Almond Flour is blanched almonds with the skin removed. I notice that my cakes and cookies are denser and more “mealy” textured, when almond meal is used.

Homemade Low Carb Almond Flour

If you are feeling like you are up for a decent challenge, you can skip buying almond flour and grind it yourself. Even though most of the directions out there say you can just grind up blanched, peeled almonds, however, I the best way to get a high quality finely blended low carb flour is to use a grain mill. If you do decide to blend this yourself make sure that you don't blend too long or you will end up with almond butter. 

Health Benefits of Almond Flour

Almonds are high in monounsaturated fats, the same type of health-promoting fats as are found in olive oil, which have been associated with reduced risk of heart disease.

Did you know that substituting nuts for an equivalent amount of carbohydrate in an average diet resulted in a 30% reduction in heart disease risk. Researchers calculated even more impressive risk reduction of 45% when fat from nuts was substituted for saturated fats. In addition to their cholesterol-lowering effects, almonds' ability to reduce heart disease risk may also be partly due to the antioxidant action of the vitamin E found in the almonds, as well as to the LDL-lowering effect of almonds' monounsaturated fats. 

People who pass on the pre-meal bread basket aren’t usually doing so because we don’t like bread. In fact, for most of us, it’s the exact opposite! As a self-proclaimed former “Carb Queen”, I’ll admit I absolutely LOVE the taste of bread. However, what I don’t love about it is:

  1. Bread lacks true nutritional value. Most breads are devoid of any real nutrients, but are “fortified/enriched” with vitamins and minerals. That means that things like calcium, vitamin E, iron, and fiber are added back into breads after their ingredients have been so highly processed that the nutrients have been stripped from them. That is cool and all, but many experts argue that the body does not absorb and utilize the nutrients that are added in the same way as it would absorb nutrients that occur naturally.
  2. Bread is packed full of junk. Think things along the lines of high fructose corn syrup, trans fats, and lots of other unpronounceable ingredients. The sugars can send your pancreas into overdrive and the preservatives can stay lodged in your stomach for years. Most breads also contain gluten which can cause bloating, stool inconsistency, damage to the wall of the intestinal tract, and tiredness. 
  3. Bread puts you on a blood sugar roller coaster. When you eat these processed carbohydrates, your blood sugar spikes and insulin levels rise then your blood sugar crashes and you feel like you need to take a nap, so you eat more carbs to bring yourself back out of the food coma. The impact on blood sugar causes the vicious cycle of eating, getting hungry, then eating again.

When I cut bread out of my diet completely a few years ago, I started to feel so much better in terms of energy levels, lack of bloating, and inflammation. At that point, I also came to the sad realization that I would likely never get to eat delicious bread again...but, thankfully, I was wrong!!

That was when I got really interested in finding alternative bread recipe options. I have tested many recipes that I found while surfing the internet and even came up with some gems of my own along the way.

Here are some of my other favorite go-to recipes:

http://insidekellyskitchen.com/recipe/perfect-protein-bread (This is honestly the perfect bread. It has actual nutritional value with 8 grams of protein and 70 calories per slice. It is great as toast, sandwich bread, croutons, and can easily be flavored with spices to make it even more tasty.)

http://insidekellyskitchen.com/recipe/whey-better-biscuits (I’m not joking when I say these are legit biscuits. The mix doesn’t come from a box, but they seriously have the Bisquick taste. I’ve used them with homemade sausage gravy and have made breakfast sandwiches with them as well.)

http://insidekellyskitchen.com/recipe/corn-free-cornbread (WHAT?! Corn-free? Yep, that’s right. I dunno about you, but I love some cornbread with my chili and this recipe totally fits the bill in terms of texture and taste. If I didn’t tell you, you’d never know it wasn’t the real thing!)

http://insidekellyskitchen.com/recipe/kellys-krazy-breadsticks (Again, tons of protein in this recipe at a whopping 10 grams per breadstick. These things are absolutely awesome dipped in tomato sauce. Serve them with a side salad and you’ve got a well balanced, delicious meal.)

http://insidekellyskitchen.com/recipe/banana-almond-bread (This recipe is made in my house at least once a month. Believe it or not, my picky 5 year old actually asks me to make it for him! Breakfast protein options are really tricky since he’s not a fan of eggs, kefir, yogurt, or cottage cheese, so this bread has been a staple on the menu. It comes in at 8.5 grams of protein per slice and has 135 calories, which makes it a pretty good way for my little guy to start the day.)

 

90 Second Almond Bread

Dietary
Sugar Free
Low Carb
Calories per serving
310 (or 290 w/ butter)
Servings
1
Ingredients

3 T almond flour
1 egg
1/2 t baking powder
1 T coconut oil (or butter), melted
spices, if desired

Directions
  1. Mix almond flour, egg, and baking powder together in microwavable container
  2. Stir in coconut oil (or butter) and spices, if desired, until well combined
  3. Microwave for 90 seconds
  4. Cool for a minute
  5. Slice in half
  6. Toast in toaster or lightly brown each side in skillet over med-high heat 

Apple Cider Gummies

This is a sweet treat made with Keto friendly ingredients and it's pretty yummy. Ha... gummy yummy! Not to mention you can get all kinds of health benefits from the Apple Cider Vinegar.

Jump To Recipe

Apple cider vinegar has various healthful properties, including antimicrobial and antioxidant effects. Studies show that apple cider vinegar can reduce the rise in your blood glucose level after a meal and help promote weight loss as part of a calorie-restricted diet. Dr. Oz recommends 1 teaspoon before or with each meal. Eating apple cider vinegar gummies before meals or right before bedtime may benefit your blood sugar levels the most. 

 

Apple cider vinegar, or cider vinegar, is a vinegar made from fermented apple juice. It's used in many recipes and has been in kitchens and pantries for a very long time.

It took a while to get used to the sour and strong taste of vinegar at first, but you start to almost love it once you get used to it. With these gummies you can forget about that sour taste and just enjoy a yummy treat. 

Here are 6 major benefits of Apple Cider Vinegar

  • It has a lot of healthy substances in it (including the "mother")
  • It's very good at ridding the gut of harmful bacteria.
  • It has been known to lower blood sugar levels
  • May aid weight loss.
  • It will help you manage diabetes while it lowers your blood sugar levels. 
  • Aids in your natural glow by boosting skin health.

For centuries, apple cider vinegar has been used as a home remedy to treat many health ailments, as well as a disinfectant and natural preservative. The best way to incorporate apple cider vinegar into your diet is to use it in cooking. It's a simple addition to foods like salad dressings and homemade mayonnaise. Some people also like to dilute it in water and drink it as a beverage. But now you can also try this recipe and eat a delicious treat!

Apple Cider Gummies

Dietary
Sugar Free
Low Carb
Calories per serving
5
Servings
24
Ingredients
  • 2 cup water
  • 1/2 cup apple cider vinegar
  • 1 tsp. liquid stevia (or more, to taste)
  • 1 tsp. cinnamon
  • 5 tbsp. gelatin
Directions
  1. Combine water, cinnamon, and stevia together in saucepan and bring to a boil.
  2. Remove saucepan from heat.
  3. Sprinkle gelatin powder over liquid and whisk until fully dissolved.
  4. Stir in apple cider vinegar.
  5. Pour mixture into silicon molds of your choosing. Here is a really cute IKK pick
  6. Chill in refrigerator for at least 1 hour before serving.
  7. Empty onto countertop or in a bowl
  8. Sprinkle on or toss in bowl with Keto friendly Monk Fruit sweetener.

Cinnamon Coffee Cake

Have a guilt free, gluten free cinnamon coffee cake with your coffee this morning. It's a low fat cinnamon coffee cake and a very healthy cinnamon coffee cake that will be sure to put a smile on your face.

Cinnamon Coffee Cake

Dietary
Sugar Free
Low Carb
Calories per serving
185
Servings
9
Ingredients

Cake:

  • 2 c. almond flour
  • 1 1/2 tsp. baking powder
  • 1/4 tsp. pink salt
  • 1/4 c. unsweetened applesauce
  • 1 1/2 tsp. vanilla
  • 1 tsp. cinnamon
  • 1/2 c. egg whites
  • 1/4 c. water

Topping:

  • 2 tsp. cinnamon
  • 1 tsp. powdered stevia
  • 2 T. coconut flour
  • 3 T. shredded unsweetened coconut
  • 2 T. chopped walnuts
  • 1 T. coconut oil
Directions
  1. Preheat oven to 350 degrees and lightly grease 8x8 inch pan.
  2. Combine almond flour, baking powder, pink salt, and cinnamon in large bowl. 
  3. Stir in applesauce, vanilla, egg whites, and water.
  4. Transfer mixture to pan and set aside.
  5. In separate bowl, combine cinnamon, stevia, coconut flour, and shredded coconut.
  6. Mash coconut oil into mixture with fork until crumbly consistency is reached.
  7. Stir in chopped walnuts.
  8. Sprinkle topping mixture onto batter and press down lightly with fork.
  9. Bake for 20-25 minutes, until toothpick inserted in center comes out clean.

General Tso Sauce II (Sugar Free)

Now you can have all of that yummy spicy General Tso's goodness without any of the sugar. Try it now and let us know what you think.

General Tso Sauce II (Sugar Free)

Dietary
Sugar Free
Low Carb
Calories per serving
145
Servings
3
Ingredients

1/4 tsp. ginger
1 T. stevia extract
1/4 tsp. xanthan gum
2 cloves garlic, minced
1/4 c. chicken broth
1/2 tsp. ghost pepper hot sauce
2 T. coconut oil
1 T. sesame oil
1/2 tsp. chili powder
1 T. rice wine vinegar
2 T. Bragg's liquid aminos

Directions
  1. Heat coconut oil in wok over med-high heat.
  2. Add garlic and cook until turning golden.
  3. Add chili powder and cook another minute.
  4. Stir in ginger, chicken broth, vinegar, stevia, liquid aminos, and sesame oil.
  5. Increase to high heat and bring to a boil.
  6. Cook, stirring occasionally, for 3 minutes.
  7. Remove from heat and stir in xanthan gum.
  8. Allow to cool slightly and thicken.

Nori Gomasio

Nori Gomasio

Dietary
Sugar Free
Low Carb
Calories per serving
55
Servings
4 (1 T each)
Ingredients

1/4 c sesame seeds
1/2 t pink salt
1 sheet toasted Nori seaweed

Directions
  1. Heat sesame seeds in skillet over low heat, stirring frequently, for 3-5 minutes, or until they turn golden brown and begin to pop
  2. Remove from heat
  3. Let cool for 10 minutes
  4. Place seeds, salt, and nori in a small food processor or blender
  5. Pulse until most seeds are cracked open (Be careful not to grind to a smooth consistency)
  6. Store in airtight container

    (Sprinkle on veggies, salad, meats, etc)

Tapioca Flour Dinner Rolls (Biscuits)

These are so fluffy and delicious. Better yet they are healthier than biscuits that you make with regular flour. Give them a try and let us know how you like them.

Tapioca Flour Dinner Rolls (Biscuits)

Dietary
Low Carb
Calories per serving
140
Servings
10
Ingredients

1 cup tapioca flour,
1/4 – 1/3 c coconut flour,
1 t pink salt,
1/2 c warm water,
1/2 c olive oil,
1 large egg, whisked

Directions
  1. Preheat oven to 350 degrees 
  2. Grease cookie sheet
  3. Combine tapioca flour with salt and 1/4 cup of coconut flour in a medium bowl
  4. Mix well
  5. Pour in oil and warm water and stir
  6. Add whisked egg and continue mixing until well combined (If mixture is too thin, add one or two more tablespoons of coconut flour until the mixture is soft but somewhat sticky dough)
  7. Scoop out about two tablespoons of the dough and roll into 10 balls (Can also be made as drop biscuits)
  8. Use extra tapioca flour in the palms of hands so dough does not stick
  9. Bake about 35 minutes, until lightly browned

Copycat Bahama Breeze Crab Stack

WELCOME. YOUR ISLAND GETAWAY BEGINS HERE!!!

Ha, just kidding. We did borrow this idea for the best jumbo lump crab stack though. If tropical tastes and gathering with friends for cocktails and island flavors is your thing, then this recipe is perfect for you. At home you won't have the the energy of live music or the feeling of sunshine on your face, but can still enjoy a taste of the Caribbean with this amazing creation.

Jump To Recipe

What is jumbo lump crab?

The large pieces of meat from the muscle that connects the crab's powerful back swimming legs are known as lump crabmeat. Jumbo lump consists of the largest of these chunks, and costs a little more than regular lump, which is made up of the broken pieces of jumbo.

What's the difference between lump and jumbo lump crab meat?

Lump and backfin are from the back body chambers of the crab, so the pieces are large and intact. Jumbo lump crabmeat is pricier and the pieces can be kept intact for cocktail presentations or in sautés, while super lump and backfin crabmeat are perfect for crab cakes, dips, or casseroles.

Why is jumbo lump crab meat so expensive?

Colossal lump crab (also known as mega jumbo or super jumbo) is the large chunks of meat that connect to the swimmer fins. There are only two of these muscles per crab, which is why it is so expensive (often $40 to $50 or more per pound). Jumbo lump crabmeat chunks are the same two muscles, just from smaller crabs.

4 Best Crab Meats in a Can

Rank Product Meat Type
1. Bumble Bee White Crab Meat White meat
2. Handy Jumbo Lump Crab Meat Jumbo lump (pasteurized)
3. Crown Prince Fancy White-Lump Crab Meat White lump meat
4. Handy Seafood Premium Lump Crab Meat Large lump + body meat

Copycat Bahama Breeze Crab Stack

Dietary
Sugar Free
Low Carb
Calories per serving
690
Servings
1
Ingredients

1 ripe Hass avocadoes, sliced
1 (3 oz) mango, chopped
1 tablespoons chopped red onions
1⁄8 jalapeno pepper, minced 
1⁄4 red bell pepper, chopped
5 ounces jumbo lump crab meat
2 tablespoon plain greek yogurt 
1/2 tablespoon capers
1/2 teaspoon coarse grain mustard
1⁄4 teaspoon Worcestershire sauce
1⁄4 lemon, juiced
1⁄4 teaspoon cajun seasoning
1/2 teaspoon minced garlic
1/2 teaspoon hot sauce

Directions
  1. Mix yogurt, capers, mustard, worcestershire sauce, lemon juice, cajun seasoning, garlic, and hot sauce then refrigerate.
  2. Use a dual open ended cylindrical mold to form the stacks. (If you don't have a mold, use an empty clean soup or veggie can with both ends removed.)
  3. Place the mold onto the serving plate.
  4. Gently push down the avocado slices into the bottom of the mold.
  5. Mix together the mango, jalapeno, red bell pepper, and red onion, then gently push down on top of the avocado layer.
  6. Gently toss the crab with the refrigerated mixture, then gently push down on top of the mango layer.
  7. Carefully slide the mold off of the stack and chill until ready to serve.
  8. Serve cold on small bed of greens.

Mini Stuffed Cabbage Rolls (mini cabbage rolls)

These mini cabbage rolls are a quick fix to satisfy that hunger craving. Try this recipe today and let us know how you like it. 

Mini Stuffed Cabbage Rolls (mini cabbage rolls)

Dietary
Oil Free
Sugar Free
Low Carb
Calories per serving
215
Servings
1
Ingredients

3.5 oz extra lean ground beef 
3 big cabbage keaves 
1 c shredded cabbage 
1/8 t onion salt 
1/8 t garlic powder 
1/8 t asian spices 
1⁄2 t stevia

Directions
  1. Cut cabbage leaves in half and steam for 5 minutes.
  2. Move leaves over to side of steamer to make room for shredded cabbage.
  3. Steam both for 5 minutes.
  4. Remove shredded cabbage to a mixing bowl.
  5. Brown your beef and add the spices to the meat.
  6. Add beef to bowl of shredded cabbage and mix.
  7. Roll into small meat balls then wrap in a cabbage leaf.
  8. Steam for another 5 minutes.

Hearty Flax Bread

Hearty Flax Bread

Dietary
Low Carb
Calories per serving
170
Servings
12
Ingredients

2 c. flax meal
1/2 c. oats
2 T. chia seeds
1/4 c. sunflower seeds
1 scoop unflavored whey protein powder
2 tsp. baking powder
4 eggs
3/4 c. unsweetened almond milk

Directions
  1. Preheat oven to 350 degrees and line loaf pan with parchment paper.
  2. Combine flax meal, oats, protein powder, chia seeds, sunflower seeds, and baking powder together in mixing bowl.
  3. In separate bowl, whisk eggs and almond milk together. 
  4. Add wet mixture to dry and mix well.
  5. Pour batter into loaf pan and sprinkle with additional seeds/oats, if desired.
  6. Bake for 30-35 minutes, until toothpick inserted in center comes out clean.
  7. Allow to cool before slicing with sharp knife.
  8. Store in fridge or freezer.

Almond Cake

Almond Cake

Dietary
Sugar Free
Low Carb
Calories per serving
235
Servings
12
Ingredients

6 T. olive oil or coconut oil (melted) 
zest of 1 orange
5 eggs, divided
1/2 tsp. pink salt
2 bananas, mashed
1 tsp. almond extract
1 tsp. vanilla extract
2 c. almond flour
1/2 c. sliced almonds
1 orange, finely chopped (optional)

Directions
  1. Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
  2. Grease 11x9 inch pan and set aside.
  3. Place egg whites in one mixing bowl and egg yolks in another.
  4. Add salt to egg whites and use mixer to beat until stiff peaks are formed then set aside.
  5. Add bananas to egg yolks and beat with mixer for 3 minutes. 
  6. Add oil, orange zest, vanilla, and almond extract and continue mixing until combined.
  7. Add almond flour and stir with spatula. 
  8. Fold in egg whites until well combined.
  9. Transfer batter to prepared pan.
  10. Sprinkle almonds on top and press lightly into batter.
  11. Bake for 30-35 minutes, until toothpick inserted in center comes out clean. 
  12. Remove from oven and allow to cool completely before serving. 
  13. Top with a spoonful of chopped orange, if desired. 

 

Easy Peezy (PB) Banana Fudge

Easy Peezy (PB) Banana Fudge

Dietary
Sugar Free
Low Carb
Calories per serving
100 (120 w/ peanut butter)
Servings
20
Ingredients

3/4 c. coconut oil, melted
1/2 c. unsweetened cocoa powder
4 bananas
OPTIONAL: 1/3 c. peanut butter (or other nut butter)
 

Directions
  1. Line 8x8 inch baking pan with foil.
  2. Place all ingredients into blender and blend until smooth.
  3. Pour mixture into lined pan then tap pan on countertop a few times to evenly distribute mixture.
  4. Place into freezer for 1 hour or until hardened.
  5. Remove from freezer and allow to thaw for a few minutes then slice into 20 squares.
  6. Store in, covered, in refrigerator (or store in freezer and allow to thaw before eating).

Sweet & Savory Turkey Pumpkin Chili

Sweet & Savory Turkey Pumpkin Chili

Dietary
Oil Free
Sugar Free
Low Carb
Calories per serving
290
Servings
1
Ingredients

4 oz. ground turkey
1 c. canned pumpkin
2 tsp. minced onion flakes
1/4 tsp. thyme
1/4 tsp. sage
1/2 tsp. cinnamon
1/8 tsp. Simple Girl Dry Bouillion
2 c. water
1 tsp. chili powder

Directions
  1. Brown turkey in saucepan over med-high heat.
  2. Add onion flakes, thyme, sage, and cinnamon and cook another couple minutes.
  3. Add pumkin, water, bouillion, and chili powder and bring to a simmer.
  4. Reduce heat and continue cooking until heated through.

Whey Better Biscuits

Whey Better Biscuits

Dietary
Sugar Free
Low Carb
Calories per serving
115
Servings
8
Ingredients

3/4 c. almond flour
1/4 c. coconut flour
1 tsp. baking powder
1/4 tsp. pink salt
1/4 c. unflavored whey protein powder
1 1/2 T. coconut oil
3/4 c. liquid egg whites

Directions
  1. Preheat oven to 375 degrees. 
  2. Line a baking sheet with parchment paper. 
  3. Mix almond flour, coconut flour, baking powder, protein powder, and salt together in large mixing bowl. 
  4. Cut in cold coconut oil with a fork until mixture is crumbly. 
  5. Place bowl in refrigerator for 10 minutes. 
  6. In separate bowl, whisk egg whites until very frothy. 
  7. Fold egg whites into chilled flour mixture until well combined. 
  8. Scoop 1/4 cup of dough onto baking sheet at a time and form into desired biscuit shape.
  9. Bake for 15 minutes or until tops are just turning golden brown. 
  10. Serve warm or store in airtight container in refrigerator.

Chocolate Chip Peanut Butter Protein Balls

Chocolate Chip Peanut Butter Protein Balls

Dietary
Low Carb
Calories per serving
50
Servings
10
Ingredients

Balls:
6 T. peanut flour
1/4 c. plain kefir
2 dropperfuls stevia
2 pinches pink salt
1 scoop pea protein powder
3 T. almond milk
1 T. cacao nibs

Coating:
1 T. coconut oil, melted
1 T. unsweetened cocoa powder
stevia, to taste

Directions
  1. Line baking sheet with wax paper or parchment paper.
  2. Combine peanut flour, stevia, and kefir to form peanut butter.
  3. Add protein powder and almond milk and continue to stir until dough-like mixture forms.
  4. Fold in cacao nibs.
  5. Roll into balls, about 1 tablespoon each, and place on baking sheet.
  6. Combine coating mixture in small bowl.
  7. Roll one ball in coating mixture then place back on baking sheet. 
  8. Repeat with each ball then place baking sheet into fridge or freezer for a few minutes until coating has hardened.
  9. Continue Step #7 and #8 until all coating mixture is gone.
  10. Store balls, covered, in fridge (May also be stored in freezer and allowed to defrost 5-10 minutes before eating).

Grain-Free Waffle II

Grain-Free Waffle II

Dietary

Directions

  5. Cook for 4 minutes.

Chocolate Cacao Nib Protein Cookies

Chocolate Cacao Nib Protein Cookies

Dietary
Sugar Free
Low Carb
Calories per serving
40
Servings
8
Ingredients

1 scoop pea protein powder
1-2 T. unsweetened cocoa powder
4 dropperfuls vanilla creme stevia
1 T. coconut flour
1/3 c. plain kefir (or milk of choice)
3 T. liquid egg whites
1 1/2 T. cacao nibs, divided

Directions
  1. Preheat oven to 350 degrees and line baking sheet with parchment paper.
  2. In small bowl, combine protein powder, coconut flour, and cocoa powder.
  3. Stir in stevia, kefir, and egg whties, until well combined.
  4. Fold in 1 tablespoon cacao nibs.
  5. Drop mixture, 1 heaping tablespoon at a time, onto baking sheet. 
  6. Top each cookie evenly with remaining cacao nibs.
  7. Bake for 12 minutes.
  8. Remove from oven and transfer to cooking rack to cool.

Homemade Bath Fizzies

Homemade Bath Fizzies

Dietary
Sugar Free
Low Carb
Calories per serving
n/a
Servings
12
Ingredients

1 c. baking soda
1/2 c. epsom salt
1/2 c. cornstarch
1/2 c. citric acid
1-2 tsp. essential oil(s) of choice
5 drops food coloing of choice (optional)
3 T. coconut oil, melted
1 1/2 T. water

Directions
  1. In large bowl, whisk together baking soda, cornstarch, epsom salt, and citric acid until well combined and clump-free.
  2. Place wet ingredients in small mason jar with lid then gently shake until well combined.
  3. Add 1 teaspoon at a time of wet mixture to dry mixture while whisking, if mixture starts to bubble....SLOW DOWN! (Once all liquid is added, mixture will be the consistency of lightly damp sand and will barely clump together.)
  4. Transfer mixture evenly into silicone molds and press down firmly until well packed.
  5. Allow mixture to sit in molds overnight or longer, until completely hardened. 
  6. Gently and carefully, pop fizzies out of molds.

Chocolate Peanut Butter No-Bake Super Cookie

Chocolate Peanut Butter No-Bake Super Cookie

Dietary
Sugar Free
Low Carb
Calories per serving
295
Servings
1
Ingredients

Base:
1 scoop pea protein powder
1-2 T. unsweetened cocoa powder
4 dropperfuls stevia
1 T. coconut flour
1/4-1/2 c. unsweetened almond milk (or kefir)

Topping:
1/2 T. melted coconut oil
1 dropperful stevia
1/2 tsp. peanut butter (or other nut butter of choice)

Directions
  1. Mix all topping ingredients together with fork in small round tupperware container.
  2. Place into freezer.
  3. In small bowl, combine protein powder, coconut flour, and cocoa powder.
  4. Stir in stevia then add milk (or kefir), one tablespoon at a time, until cookie dough consistency is reached.
  5. Transfer dough to a piece of parchment paper and press into desired cookie shape and thickness.
  6. Take hardened topping mixture out of freezer and break into pieces.
  7. Press topping pieces gently into cookie.
  8. Place cookie into freezer for 30 minutes, or until desired firmness is reached. 
  9. Store in freezer and allow to sit at room temperature or in fridge until desired firmness is reached before eating.

Greek Yogurt Cheesecake

Jump To Recipe

This is excellent served on it's own or with a dallop of Blueberry Topping!

Greek Yogurt Cheesecake

Dietary
Low Carb
Calories per serving
250
Servings
8
Ingredients

Crust:
1/4 c. coconut oil
1 1/2 c. almond flour
1-2 tsp. cinnamon
1 T. honey or IMO syrup
1/2 tsp. pink salt

Filling:
2 c. plain Greek yogurt
2 eggs
1/4 c. honey or IMO syrup
1 tsp. vanilla extract
Pinch of pink salt

Directions
  1. Preheat oven to 350 degrees and lightly grease 9 inch pie plate.
  2. Using fork, stir pie crust ingredients together until combined.
  3. Transfer mixture to pie plate and gently spread and pack with hands.
  4. Bake for 10 minutes then remove from oven.
  5. Increase oven temperature to 375 degrees.
  6. Prepare a water bath by pouring enough water into baking pan to cover 1 inch of the sides.
  7. Mix together yogurt and honey (or IMO syrup) in bowl.
  8. Whisk in eggs, vanilla, and salt.
  9. Pour mixture on top of pie crust and spread evenly.
  10. Place pie pan into water bath and bake for 1 hour or until pie is just slightly jiggly.
  11. Turn off oven, crack door, and allow cheesecake to set for 15-20 minutes.
  12. Remove from oven and allow cheesecake to cool to room temp.
  13. Refrigerate for at least 2 hours before serving.

Cottage Cheese Bagels (or Muffins)

Cottage Cheese Bagels (or Muffins)

Dietary
Sugar Free
Low Carb
Calories per serving
160 (or 80)
Servings
6 bagels (or 12 muffins)
Ingredients
  • 1 1/2 c. 4% cottage cheese
  • 1 1/8 c. egg whites
  • 6 T. almond flour
  • 3 T. coconut flour
  • 1 tsp. baking powder
  • 1/4 tsp. pink salt
  • 1 1/2 scoops unflavored whey protein powder
Directions
  1. Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
  2. Combine cottage cheese and egg whites in blender until smooth.
  3. Add in almond flour, coconut flour, baking powder, salt, and protein powder and process until combined.
  4. Pour evenly into silicone bagel tray or muffin tins.
  5. Bake for 30-40 minutes, until beginning to slightly brown on top. 
  6. Remove from oven and allow to cool before removing from tray. 

Buffalo Chicken Omelette

Jump To Recipe

Buffalo chicken in any form is a go-to favorite in my house and I personally love, love, love omelettes, so I decided to combine the two this morning for brunch. The result was the absolutely delicious creation! By using just one whole egg along with egg whites, I was able to keep the calorie count reasonable and still have a nice sized omelette end up on the plate. 

 

Also, as a side note, if you have never cooked your eggs in coconut oil before, I highly recommend you try it. Coconut oil is great to use when cooking at high-heat temperatures since it doesn't oxidize in the pan and has added health benefits. On top of that, eggs cooked in coconut oil seem to come out fluffier, shinier, and with a slightly sweet taste!

Buffalo Chicken Omelette

Dietary
Sugar Free
Low Carb
Calories per serving
405
Servings
1
Ingredients

1 egg 
1/2 c. egg whites
1 T. melted coconut oil, divided
1 tsp. lemon juice
1 T. hot sauce
1 tsp. dijon mustard
1-4 tsp. water
1/8 tsp. coconut aminos
2 pinches oregano
2 pinches garlic powder
2 oz. cooked chicken breast
1/2 green pepper, finely chopped
2 T. chopped red onion
2 T. feta cheese
pink salt and pepper, to taste

Directions
  1. Place 1/2 tablespoon coconut oil, lemon juice, coconut aminos, garlic powder, oregano, hot sauce, and dijon mustard together in container with lid and shake until well combined.
  2. Add water until desired consistency is reached then set aside.
  3. Heat remaining coconut oil in skillet over medium heat.
  4. Add peppers and onions to skillet and cook until tender.
  5. Cut chicken breast into small cubes and place in bowl.
  6. Stir in 1 tablespoon of hot sauce mixture along with peppers and onions. 
  7. Whisk together egg, egg whites, salt and pepper and pour into skillet.
  8. Once eggs are mostly cooked, sprinkle chicken and veggie mixture onto eggs.
  9. Top with 1 1/2 tablespoons feta then fold egg into desired omelette shape.
  10. Place omelette onto plate.
  11. Top with remaining 1/2 tablespoon feta and any filling that fell out in skillet.
  12. Drizzle hot sauce mixture over top of omelette.

Simple Spinach Balls

Enjoy these healthy simple spinach balls for a quick snack or as an Hors d'oeuvre. Put these out on a tray and you can kiss them all goodbye! Try out this recipe now and let us know how you like them. 

Simple Spinach Balls

Dietary
Oil Free
Sugar Free
Low Carb
Calories per serving
205 (~13/ball)
Servings
1 batch
Ingredients
  • 1 (10 oz.) package frozen chopped spinach, defrosted
  • 1 egg
  • 1/2 c. egg whites
  • 1/2 tsp. garlic powder
  • 1/2 tsp. onion powder
  • 1/4 tsp. sage
  • 1/4 tsp. thyme
  • pinch of nutmeg
  • pink salt and pepper, to taste
Directions
  1. Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
  2. Drain spinach to remove as much moisture as possible then place in bowl and set aside.
  3. Whisk together egg, egg whites, and spices.
  4. Pour egg mixture into spinach and mix together until well combined.
  5. Spoon 16 heaping tablespoon mounds into silicone mini muffin tray.
  6. Bake for 20 minutes.
  7. Allow to cool slightly before removing from tray.

Banana Almond Bread

Banana Almond Bread

Dietary
Sugar Free
Low Carb
Calories per serving
110
Servings
12
Ingredients

3 bananas 
3 eggs
1/2 c. egg whites
1 c. almond flour
1/4 c. pea protein powder or 1/2 c. whey protein powder
1 tsp. baking powder
1 tsp. cinnamon

Directions
  1. Preheat oven to 350 degrees and line loaf pan with parchment paper.
  2. Combine bananas, eggs, and egg whites in blender.
  3. Pulse in baking powder, cinnamon, almond flour, and protein powder until well combined, scraping sides of blender with spatula as needed.
  4. Pour mixture into loaf pan and bake for 55-65 minutes, until loaf top starts to brown and toothpick inserted in center comes out clean.
  5. Allow loaf to cool completely before slicing with sharp knife.

Banana Oat Bagels

Banana Oat Bagels

Dietary
Low Carb
Calories per serving
150
Servings
6
Ingredients

2 bananas
2 eggs
6 T. egg whites
1 tsp. baking powder
3/4 tsp. cinnamon
1/4 c. pea protein powder
1 1/4 c. + 1 T. oats (divided)

Directions
  1. Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
  2. Pulse 1 1/4 cups oats, protein powder, cinnamon, and baking powder in blender until flour-like consistency is reached.
  3. Add bananas, egg, and egg whites to blender and process until combined.
  4. Spoon batter evenly into silicone bagel tray.
  5. Sprinkle 1/2 teaspoon of reserved oats onto each bagel and press slightly into batter.
  6. Bake for 20-25 minutes.
  7. Remove from oven and allow to cool for 10 minutes before removing from bagel tray.

Crockpot Lemon Chicken and Sauerkraut

Crockpot Lemon Chicken and Sauerkraut

Dietary
Oil Free
Sugar Free
Low Carb
Calories per serving
220
Servings
4
Ingredients

1 (27 oz. can) sauerkraut
1/4 tsp. cayenne pepper
1/2 tsp. thyme
1 1/2 lb. chicken breast, sliced 1/2 inch thick
3 T. lemon juice
pink salt and pepper, to taste

Directions
  1. Place sauerkraut in the crockpot.
  2. Stir cayenne and thyme into sauerkraut.
  3. Place chicken on top.
  4. Brush lemon juice onto chicken (flipping to get both sides).
  5. Sprinkle with pink salt and pepper.
  6. Cook on high 4-5 hours or low 6-7 hours.

Garlic Dill Roasted Carrots

Dietary

Ingredients

Directions

Buffalo Chicken

Buffalo Chicken

Dietary
Sugar Free
Low Carb
Calories per serving
375
Servings
1
Ingredients

4 oz. grilled or baked chicken breast
1/2 T. coconut oil, melted
1 tsp. lemon juice

Cajun Roasted Brussels Sprouts

Cajun Roasted Brussels Sprouts

Dietary
Sugar Free
Low Carb
Calories per serving
185
Servings
4
Ingredients

2 lbs. brussels sprouts
3 T. coconut oil, melted
2 tsp. Cajun Seasoning

Directions
  1. Preheat oven to 400 degrees and line baking sheet with parchment paper.
  2. Remove ends of brussels sprouts and cut each in half.
  3. Place brussels sprouts, oil, and seasoning in large resealable plastic bag.
  4. Seal bag tightly and shake until sprouts are coated.
  5. Pour evenly onto baking sheet and place in oven.
  6. Roast for 25-30 minutes, shaking pan every 5 to 7 minutes for even browning (reduce heat, if necessary, to prevent burning).

Mexican Skillet

Mexican Skillet

Dietary
Sugar Free
Low Carb
Calories per serving
315
Servings
2
Ingredients

1/2 lb. lean ground beef
1/2 red onion, coarsely chopped
1 green pepper, coarsely chopped
6 jalapeno pepper slices, finely chopped
4 c. riced cauliflower
1 tsp. chili powder
1/2 tsp. paprika
1/2 tsp. garlic powder
1 tsp. cumin
1/2 c. salsa
 

Directions
  1. Cook beef in skillet over medium-high heat until beginning to brown.
  2. Stir in peppers, onion, and cauliflower then cover with lid and cook, stirring occasionally, until veggies begin to soften.
  3. Stir in spices and salsa and cook for another couple minutes. 
  4. Portion into 2 bowls.

*Excellent topped with sour cream/plain greek yogurt and guacamole

Vanilla Sheet Cake

Vanilla Sheet Cake

Dietary
Low Carb
Calories per serving
95 (110 w/ honey)
Servings
8
Ingredients

4 eggs
1/4 c. IMO syrup (or honey)
1/3 c. coconut flour
1/3 c. almond flour
1/2 tsp. baking powder
1/8 tsp. pink salt
1 tsp. vanilla extract
2 dropperfuls vanilla stevia (optional)

Directions
  1. Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
  2. Line 11x7 inch baking pan with parchment paper or lightly grease.
  3. In food processor, mix eggs. IMO syrup (or honey), vanilla, and stevia, if desired.
  4. Stir together salt, almond flour, coconut flour, and baking powder until combined.
  5. Pour wet mixture into dry and stir until incorporated.
  6. Transfer mixture into baking pan and spread evenly with spatula.
  7. Bake for 15-20 minutes or until a toothpick comes out clean when inserted.
  8. Remove from oven and allow to cool completely.
  9. Top with frosting of choice, if desired.

    (Frosting shown in photo is Chocolate Ganache with some almond extract added to it for a Chocolate Cherry Frosting, which added an additional 10 calories per serving.)

No-Bake Pumpkin Spice Bars

No-Bake Pumpkin Spice Bars

Dietary
Low Carb
Calories per serving
150 (160 w/ honey)
Servings
12
Ingredients

2 ½ c. oats
2 scoops vanilla protein powder of choice
1 c. canned pumpkin
¼ c. nut butter of choice
¼ c. IMO syrup (or honey)
1 T. vanilla extract
1 tsp. ginger
½ tsp. cinnamon
½ tsp. nutmeg
¼ tsp. cloves

Drizzle:
2 T. coconut oil, melted
1 T. cinnamon (or unsweetened cocoa powder)
4 dropperfuls stevia

Directions
  1. Line 8x8 inch baking dish with parchment paper.
  2. Pulse oats and protein powder in food processor until flour-like consistency is reached.
  3. Add all other ingredients and process until dough forms.
  4. Press mixture into baking dish evenly.
  5. Place in freezer for 1 hour.
  6. Remove from freezer and cut in 12 rectangles using sharp knife. 
  7. Combine coconut oil, cinnamon/cocoa, and stevia.
  8. Drizzle over bars then place into fridge for topping to harden.
  9. Store in fridge or freezer.

Eggplant French Toast

Eggplant French Toast

Dietary
Sugar Free
Low Carb
Calories per serving
150
Servings
2
Ingredients

1 large (or 2 small) eggplant
2 eggs
3 T. almond milk
½ tsp. vanilla extract
¼ tsp. cinnamon, plus more for dusting
stevia, to taste (optional)
oconut oil, as needed (to grease pan)

Directions
  1. Peel eggplant and slice into ¼ inch slices.
  2. Sprinkle both sides of each eggplant slice with salt.
  3. Place eggplant slices in colander and set aside for 10-20 minutes.
  4. Rinse eggplant slices well then pat dry with paper towels.
  5. Pierce eggplant slices, on each side, a few times with fork.
  6. Lightly grease skillet over medium heat.
  7. In shallow bowl, whisk together eggs, milk, vanilla, cinnamon, and stevia, if desired.
  8. Dunk eggplant slice in egg mixture then place in skillet. 
  9. Transfer slice to skillet and cook 2-3 minutes, until golden brown on one side.
  10. Flip and cook other side another 2-3 minutes, until golden brown.
  11. Repeat with remaining eggplant slices.
  12. Dip each eggplant slice again and cook another minute on each side.
  13. Sprinkle with cinnamon, if desired, and serve warm. 

Savory Pumpkin Egg Bread

This savory pumpkin egg bread is very yummy. It has just the right amount of spices to create that perfect pumpkin spice delight. Try it now and let us know what you think.

Savory Pumpkin Egg Bread

Dietary
Oil Free
Sugar Free
Low Carb
Calories per serving
50
Servings
4
Ingredients
  • 1 egg
  • 9 T. liquid egg whites
  • 1/2 c. canned pumpkin
  • 1/2 tsp. thyme
  • 1/4 tsp. sage
  • 1/4 tsp. minced onion flakes
  • 1/4 tsp. minced garlic flakes
  • pink salt and pepper, to taste
Directions
  1. Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
  2. Whisk together egg, egg whites, pumpkin, and spices until well combined.
  3. Pour batter into silicone loaf pan or an oven safe iron skillet.
  4. Bake for 50-60 minutes. 
  5. Remove from oven and allow to cool completely.

Optional Steps for a crispier bread. 

  1. Preheat toaster oven.
  2. Slice into even slices using a pizza cutter.
  3. Sit all slices onto parchment paper then place in toaster oven for 10 minutes or until starting to brown.
  4. Remove from toaster oven and place on wire rack to cool.

Fruit Gummies

Fruit Gummies

Dietary
Sugar Free
Low Carb
Calories per serving
10 (15 w/ IMO, 20 w/ honey)
Servings
16
Ingredients

1 c. berries (or other fruit) of choice
1/4 c. water
1/2 T. lemon juice (optional)
1/2 tsp. liquid stevia (or 2 T. IMO syrup or honey)
3 T. gelatin

Directions
  1. Place fruit and water in food processor and puree until smooth.
  2. Pour mixture, through strainer, into saucepan over low heat.
  3. Stir in lemon juice and sweetener of choice.
  4. Sprinkle gelatin on top and whisk until dissolved and well incorporated, about 2-3 minutes.
  5. Pour mixture evenly into 2 (8 count) silicone candy molds.
  6. Place in freezer for 25 minutes. 
  7. Pop gummies out of molds and store in sealed container in fridge.

Mock Mallo Cups

Mock Mallo Cups

Dietary
Sugar Free
Low Carb
Calories per serving
170
Servings
6
Ingredients

Bottom:
1 T. coconut oil
1/2 oz. unsweetened or semi-sweet Baker’s chocolate
1/2 T. unsweetened cocoa powder
1/4 tsp. vanilla stevia
2-3 Healthy Marshmallows

Top:
3 T. coconut oil
1 1/2 T. unsweetened cocoa powder
2 oz. unsweetened or semi-sweet Baker's chocolate
2 T. shredded unsweetened coconut 
3/4 tsp. vanilla stevia

Directions
  1. Line cupcake tin with 6 liners.
  2. Melt coconut oil and chocolate for bottom layer together in small saucepan or in microwave.
  3. Stir in cocoa powder and stevia.
  4. Pour 1 teaspoon of mixture into each cupcake tin then place in freezer for 5 minutes.
  5. Slice each marshmallow into thirds and trim edges to make circle.
  6. Remove tray from freezer.
  7. Place small dab of chocolate mixture on bottom of each marshmallow slice then place in cupcake tins.
  8. Return to freezer for 2-3 minutes.
  9. Melt coconut oil and chocolate for top layer together in small saucepan or in microwave.
  10. Stir in cocoa powder, coconut, and stevia.
  11. Pour mixture evenly into cupcake tins.
  12. Place in freezer for 5-10 minutes, until chocolate has hardened completely.
  13. Store in fridge or freezer.

Eggcellent Protein Pancakes

Healthy Marshmallows (or Healthy Marshmallow Fluff)

Healthy Marshmallows (or Healthy Marshmallow Fluff)

Dietary
Sugar Free
Low Carb
Calories per serving
5 (10 w/ IMO, 15 w/ honey)
Servings
18
Ingredients

3 T. gelatin
1/2 c. cold water
1/2 c. hot water
3/4 tsp. liquid stevia (or 3 T. IMO syrup or honey) or more, to taste
1 tsp. vanilla extract

Directions
  1. Lightly grease or line loaf pan.
  2. Gently whisk gelatin and cold water together in bowl of stand mixer until combined.
  3. Allow gel to form by sitting mixture aside for 10 minutes.
  4. Place hot water in small saucepan and bring to a slight boil.
  5. Remove from heat and stir in vanilla and stevia (or other sweetener of choice).
  6. Turn mixer on to low speed and slowly pour hot liquid down side of bowl into gelatin mixture.
  7. Increase speed to medium-high and beat for 1-2 minutes.
  8. Increase speed to high and continue to beat until mixture is fluffy and soft peaks just begin to form, about 10-14 minutes (or 6-10 minutes if using other sweetener) being VERY careful not to overbeat. 
  9. Use mixture immediately for Marshmallow Fluff or pour mixture into loaf pan, tap on countertop a few times to evenly distribute, then allow marshmallows to set, uncovered, for a few hours or overnight.
  10. Cut into 18 squares using sharp knife.
  11. Store in airtight container at room temp or in fridge. 

Eggcellent Protein Waffle

Eggcellent Protein Waffle

Dietary
Sugar Free
Low Carb
Calories per serving
275
Servings
1
Ingredients

2 eggs
3 T. liquid egg whites 
1 T. milk of choice
2 T. unflavored whey (or pea) protein powder
1/4 tsp. baking powder
2 T. coconut flour

Directions
  1. Whisk together eggs, egg whites, protein powder, milk, and baking powder.
  2. Stir in coconut flour.
  3. Pour batter evenly into waffle iron.
  4. Cook for 4 minutes. 

Perfect Protein Bread

Jump To Recipe

If you're planning to use this as sandwich bread, I would recommend to slice it thinner. I actually use a very sharp knife to cut 28-32 slices. Of course you could use the thicker slices for a sandwich as well, but it tends to drown out the flavors of the sandwich since it is such a dense bread!

Perfect Protein Bread

Dietary
Sugar Free
Low Carb
Calories per serving
85
Servings
16
Ingredients

1/2 c. pea protein powder
1/2 c. unflavored whey protein powder
3/4 c. almond flour (or 1 1/2 c. oats)
1/2 tsp. pink salt
1/2 tsp. baking soda
1/4 c. flax seed (or 6 T. flax meal)
2 c. liquid egg whites
Toppings: sesame seeds, onion flakes, poppy seeds, minced garlic, rosemary, pumpkin seeds etc. (optional)

Directions
  1. Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
  2. Pulse all dry ingredients in blender until flour-like consistency is reached.
  3. Add egg whites and blend (or transfer to large bowl and whisk) until well combined.
  4. Pour batter into silicone loaf pan or parchment lined loaf pan.
  5. Sprinkle top with toppings of choice, if desired.
  6. Bake for 45 mins.
  7. Remove from oven and slice with sharp knife. 

Homemade Paleo Fish Sticks

Homemade Paleo Fish Sticks

Dietary
Sugar Free
Low Carb
Calories per serving
245
Servings
4
Ingredients

1 lb. cod
1/2 c. almond flour
1/4 c. flax meal
1 T. onion powder
1 T. garlic powder
1 T. minced onion flakes
1/4 tsp. pink salt
1 tsp. turmeric 
1/8 tsp. pepper
1/2 c. coconut oil, melted

Directions
  1. Preheat oven to 425 degrees.
  2. Slice cod into strips about 1 inch thick.
  3. In large ziploc bag, shake flax meal, almond flour and spices until well combined.
  4. Pour melted coconut oil into shallow dish.
  5. Dip fish strip into coconut oil then place into ziploc back.
  6. Repeat with 4 more fish strips.
  7. Shake bag until strips are well coated.
  8. Transfer coated fish sticks onto lightly greased baking sheet.
  9. Repeat process with remaining fish strips.
  10. Discard extra coconut oil.
  11. Bake fish sticks for 25 minutes. 

Grain-Free Brownies

Grain-Free Brownies

Dietary
Sugar Free
Low Carb
Calories per serving
60
Servings
9
Ingredients

3 T. liquid egg whites
1 c. canned pumpkin
2 T. coconut oil, melted
1 tsp. vanilla extract
2 tsp. liquid stevia
1 c. unsweetened cocoa powder
1/2 tsp. baking soda
pinch of pink salt

Directions
  1. Preheat oven to 350 degrees and line 8x8 inch baking dish with parchment paper.
  2. In large bowl, combine egg whites, pumpkin, coconut oil, stevia, and vanilla extract.
  3. Add cocoa powder, baking powder, and pink salt and mix until smooth.
  4. Transfer to baking dish using rubber spatula and smooth mixture out evenly.
  5. Bake for 25-30 minutes.
  6. Let cool completely in baking dish (at least 1 hour) before cutting into squares.

Zucchini Fritters

Zucchini Fritters

Dietary
Sugar Free
Low Carb
Calories per serving
115
Servings
4
Ingredients

1 medium zucchini, shredded
1/4 tsp. pink salt
1 egg
1 T. minced onion flakes
2 tsp. parsley
1 T. fresh chopped chives
1/4 tsp. garlic powder
1/8 tsp. pepper
2 T. almond flour
1 T. coconut flour
2 T. coconut oil 

Directions
  1. Sprinkle shredded zucchini with pink salt and allow to sit in collander for 10 minutes.
  2. Gently press on zucchini with hands to allow water to drain.
  3. Transfer zucchini to bowl and stir in egg, spices, and flours.
  4. Heat coconut oil in skillet over medium-high heat. 
  5. Scoop 1/4 cup of zucchini mixture at a time into skillet and flatten into even circle with spatula. 
  6. Allow to cook for 2-3 minutes, until golden brown.
  7. Flip and cook another 2-3 minutes, until golden brown.

Chocolate Chip Coconut Truffles

Chocolate Chip Coconut Truffles

Dietary
Sugar Free
Low Carb
Calories per serving
40
Servings
9
Ingredients

1 c. canned pumpkin
2 T. coconut flour
1/4 c. unsweetened cocoa powder
2 dropperfuls stevia
1 T. mini chocolate chips (or COcolate chips for sugar free version)
3 T. shredded unsweetened coconut

Directions
  1. Stir pumpkin, coconut flour, cocoa powder, and stevia together in bowl until well combined.
  2. Fold in mini chocolate chips.
  3. Place coconut in small, shallow bowl.
  4. Using small cookie scoop or spoon, portion out a ball using about 2 tablespoons of pumpkin mixture.
  5. Drop ball into shredded coconut and gently roll until evenly coated, pressing softly to ensure coconut sticks to ball.
  6. Place truffle on parchement or foil lined dinner plate.
  7. Repeat with remaining pumpkin mixture.
  8. Place into freezer for 2-3 hours, until desired firmness is reached then serve immediately (or store in freezer and allow to defrost at room temp for an hour or until desired firmness is reached).

Homemade Cheez-Its

Homemade Cheez-Its

Dietary
Sugar Free
Low Carb
Calories per serving
190
Servings
7 (10 crackers/serving)
Ingredients

1 3/4 c. almond flour
3 T. nutritional yeast
1 T. coconut oil, melted
1/2 tsp. pink salt
1 egg
2 T. apple cider vinegar

Directions
  1. Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
  2. Combine almond flour, pink salt and nutritional yeast in bowl.
  3. In separate bowl, whisk together egg, coconut oil, and vinegar.
  4. Pour wet ingredients into dry ingredient bowl and stir until dough forms.
  5. Place dough between two sheets of parchment paper and use rolling pin to flatten to about ⅛ inch thickness.
  6. Cut dough into 10 rows of 7 squares using sharp knife or pizza cutter.
  7. Re-roll remaining, outer edges, of dough and cut into 7 additional squares.
  8. Sprinkle crackers with additional pink salt, if desired.
  9. Slide bottom piece of parchment and crackers onto baking sheet.
  10. Bake for 12-15 minutes, until golden (Outer crackers will brown faster, so be sure to browned crackers and continue baking remaining crackers until all are golden).

 

Dark Chocolate Mint (or Cherry) Brownies

Dark Chocolate Mint (or Cherry) Brownies

Dietary
Sugar Free
Low Carb
Calories per serving
65 (60 w/ egg whites)
Servings
9
Ingredients

1 egg (or 3 T. liquid egg whites*)
1 c. canned pumpkin
2 T. coconut oil, melted
1/2-1 tsp. peppermint (or almond) extract**
1/2 tsp. vanilla extract
2 tsp. liquid stevia
1 c. unsweetened cocoa powder
1/2 tsp. baking soda
pinch of pink salt

Directions
  1. Preheat oven to 350 degrees and line 8x8 inch baking dish with parchment paper.
  2. In large bowl, combine egg, pumpkin, coconut oil, stevia, and extracts.
  3. Add cocoa powder, baking powder, and pink salt and mix until smooth.
  4. Transfer to baking dish using rubber spatula and smooth mixture out evenly.
  5. Bake for 25-30 minutes.
  6. Let cool completely in baking dish (at least 1 hour) before cutting into squares.

    *Egg whites make brownies more fluffy/cake-like while whole egg is more dense.
    **Omit peppermint (or cherry) extract for plain brownies. 
     

Thai Green Curry Sauce

Thai Green Curry Sauce

Dietary
Sugar Free
Low Carb
Calories per serving
280
Servings
3
Ingredients

1 T. coconut oil
1 onion, chopped
2 tsp. minced garlic
1 (4 oz) can chopped green chiles
1 1/2 T. ginger
1/4 tsp. coriander
1/4 tsp. cumin
zest of 1 lemon
1/4 c. fresh basil leaves, chopped
1 dropperful stevia
2 tsp. coconut aminos
1 c. canned coconut cream
5-10 baby spinach leaves

Directions
  1. Heat coconut oil in small saucepain.
  2. Saute onion, garlic, ginger and chiles for a few minutes.
  3. Add coriander, cumin, lemon zest, and basil and cook a few more minutes.
  4. Stir in stevia, aminos, and coconut cream.
  5. Transfer sauce to blender then add spinach and process until smooth.
  6. Return to saucepan to reaheat, if needed.

Copycat Chang's Chicken Lettuce Wraps

Copycat Chang's Chicken Lettuce Wraps

Dietary
Sugar Free
Low Carb
Calories per serving
320
Servings
4
Ingredients

1 T. sesame oil
1 T. coconut oil
1 lb. ground chicken
1 medium vidalia onion, diced
1 red pepper, diced
1/4 c. coconut aminos or Bragg's liquid aminos
1 dropperful stevia
1 T. rice wine vinegar
1 T. minced garlic
1/2 tsp. cayenne pepper
1 tsp. cumin
1 tsp. ginger
1 (8 oz) can chopped water chestnuts
4 scallions, sliced
pink salt and pepper, to taste
1/2 tsp. xanthan gum (optional)
1 head butter lettuce
 

Directions
  1. Heat oils in large skillet over med-high heat.
  2. Cook chicken until crumbly.
  3. Stir in onion, pepper, garlic, cayenne pepper, cumin, and ginger and cook for 5 minutes.
  4. Stir in water chestnuts, green onions, aminos, salt, pepper, stevia and cook until sauce begins to thicken.
  5. Whisk xanthan gum into sauce then remove from burner and allow to cool and thicken for a couple minutes. 
  6. Serve with lettuce leaves.

Red White & Blue Streusel Coffee Cake

Red White & Blue Streusel Coffee Cake

Dietary
Low Carb
Calories per serving
180 (195 w/ honey)
Servings
12
Ingredients

1 1/4 c. almond flour
1/4 c. oat flour
3 T. coconut flour 
1/4 tsp. pink salt
1 tsp. cinnamon (divided)
1/2 tsp. ginger (divided)
1/3 c. IMO fiber (or honey)
3 T. coconut oil (divided)
2 T. plain Greek yogurt
1/2 c. chopped walnuts
1/2 tsp. baking soda
1/2 tsp. baking powder
2 eggs
1 tsp. vanilla extract
½ c. unsweetened applesauce
2 dropperfuls stevia
1/2 c. cranberries
1/2 c. blueberries

Directions
  1. Preheat oven to 325 degrees.
  2. Grease 8"x8" baking pan or line with parchment paper.
  3. In food processor, pulse almond flour, oat flour, coconut flour, salt, ½ teaspoon cinnamon, and ¼ teaspoon ginger until combined.
  4. Add 2 tablespoons melted coconut oil, IMO fiber/honey, and Greek yogurt, and pulse until well combined.
  5. Transfer mixture to large bowl and set aside.
  6. For the topping, return ½ cup of flour mixture to food processor.
  7. Add walnuts, remaining coconut oil, and additional cinnamon and ginger, and pulse to combine and form loose crumbs.
  8. Stir baking soda and baking powder into large bowl of dry mixture.
  9. Add eggs, vanilla, stevia, and applesauce and stir until smooth.
  10. Fold in cranberries and blueberries.
  11. Pour batter into prepared pan.
  12. Sprinkle pecan crumb mixture evenly over top of batter and press down slightly.
  13. Bake 50-60 minutes, until toothpick inserted in middle comes out clean.
  14. Cool cake completely.
  15. Store, covered, in the refrigerator for up to 4 days.

Sweet 'n Spicy Caribbean Dressing

Sweet 'n Spicy Caribbean Dressing

Dietary
Oil Free
Sugar Free
Low Carb
Calories per serving
15

Flax Tortilla Chips

Flax Tortilla Chips

Dietary
Sugar Free
Low Carb
Calories per serving
140
Servings
4
Ingredients

1 c. flax meal
1/4 - 1/3 c. water
pink salt, to taste

Directions
  1. Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
  2. Over medium heat, stir together flax meal and water with spatula for 1 minute.
  3. Remove from heat and push mixture together to form dough.
  4. Transfer dough onto piece of parchment paper on flat surface.
  5. Place second sheet of parchment paper over top of dough and use rolling pin to roll dough into a very thin sheet.
  6. Use pizza cutter to cut dough into 48 equal triangles or squares.
  7. Sprinkle pink salt liberally over top of dough.
  8. Gently transfer dough slices onto parchment lined baking sheet.
  9. Bake for 12-15 minutes then turn oven off and allow to sit inside for 5 minutes longer.
  10. Remove from oven and allow to cool.
  11. Store in airtight container.

Pumpkin Custard Pie Cups

Oil Free

Directions

Breadless Pumpkin French Toast

Start your day without carbs and switch to high quality protein with this incredibly delicious keto substitute for french toast. Only this pumpkin season make it with pumpkin pie spice! 

Breadless Pumpkin French Toast

Dietary
Oil Free
Sugar Free
Low Carb
Calories per serving
190
Servings
1
Ingredients

1 egg
1/2 c. liquid egg whites
1/2 c. pumpkin puree
1/2 tsp. pumpkin pie spice
2 dropperfuls SweetLeaf stevia 
cinnamon, optional

Directions
  1. Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
  2. Combine egg, egg whites, pumpkin, pie spice, and stevia in blender until well combined.
  3. Pour batter into silicone loaf pan.
  4. Sprinkle cinnamon lightly on top.
  5. Bake for 40-45 minutes (or microwave 6-8 minutes).
  6. Remove from oven and allow to cool slightly.
  7. Slice in half, to make 2 equal rectangles, then slice each diagonally to form 4 triangular slices.
  8. Place slices in toaster oven on a piece of parchment paper or foil and toast until lightly browned.

*Excellent served with Mock Pancake Syrup

Kelly's Krazy Belgian Waffle

Kelly's Krazy Belgian Waffle

Dietary
Sugar Free
Low Carb
Calories per serving
350
Servings
1
Ingredients

1/2 c. cottage cheese
1 egg
3 T. liquid egg whites
2 T. water
3 T. coconut flour
1/2 scoop whey protein powder
heaping 1/4 tsp. baking powder
1/8 tsp. pink salt
1/8 tsp. cinnamon (optional)

Directions
  1. Preheat waffle iron.
  2. Combine eggs and cottage cheese together in blender. 
  3. Pulse or stir in baking powder, salt, protein powder, cinnamon, water, and coconut flour until well combined, scraping sides with spatula.
  4. Scoop batter into waffle iron and spread evenly with spatula.
  5. Cook for 4 minutes.

Kelly's Krazy Bagels

Kelly's Krazy Bagels

Dietary
Sugar Free
Low Carb
Calories per serving
125
Servings
6
Ingredients

1 c. cottage cheese
3 eggs
1/4 c. almond flour
2 T. coconut flour
3/4 tsp. baking powder
1/4 tsp. pink salt
1 scoop unflavored whey protein powder

Directions
  1. Preheat oven to 350 degrees and lightly grease bagel tray.
  2. Combine eggs and cottage cheese together in blender. 
  3. Pulse or stir in baking powder, salt, and protein powder until well combined, scraping sides with spatula.
  4. Transfer to bowl/pyrex measuring up with pour spout and stir in almond flour and coconut flour.
  5. Pour/scoop batter evenly into silicone bagel tray and spread flat with spatula.

Turkey Sausage Spinach Bowl

Turkey Sausage Spinach Bowl

Dietary
Oil Free
Sugar Free
Low Carb
Calories per serving
220
Servings
1
Ingredients

4 oz. ground turkey
1 (10 oz.) box frozen chopped spinach
1/2 c. water
1/4 tsp. minced garlic flakes
1/4 tsp. minced onion flakes
1/2 tsp. sage
1/4 tsp. thyme
1/4 tsp. fennel
1/8 tsp. cinnamon
pinch nutmeg and cayenne
pink salt and pepper, to taste
1 dropperful SweetLeaf english toffee stevia

Directions
  1. Cook turkey in skillet until beginning to brown then set aside.
  2. Add water to skillet and bring to a boil.
  3. Add spinach to skillet then cover, reduce heat, and simmer for 10 minutes or until water is almost gone.
  4. Stir in all spices, stevia, and turkey and cook another 5 minutes.

Gobble 'Em Up Turkey Nuggets

Gobble 'Em Up Turkey Nuggets

Dietary
Sugar Free
Low Carb
Calories per serving
235
Servings
2 (6 nuggets each)
Ingredients

8 oz. ground turkey
2 T. flax meal
2 T. coconut flour
spices of choice, optional

Directions
  1. Preheat oven to 350 degrees and line baking sheet with parchment paper.
  2. Combine flax meal, coconut flour, and desired spices in shallow bowl.
  3. Divide turkey into 12 equal portions.
  4. Roll one portion into a ball then flatten into nugget shape.
  5. Place nugget into flax mixture.
  6. Gently flip nugget to coat other side then place on baking sheet.
  7. Repeat with remaining meat.
  8. Bake for 15 minutes.
  9. Remove from oven then flip each nugget and flatten with spatula.
  10. Return to oven and bake for 15 more minutes.

Servings
8

Kelly's Kosmic Fudge Brownies

Kelly's Kosmic Fudge Brownies

Dietary
Low Carb
Calories per serving
135 (or 150 w/ honey)
Servings
16
Ingredients

Brownies:
1/2 c. oats 
2 T. unsweetened cocoa powder
1/2 c. IMO syrup (or honey)
1 (14 oz.) can black beans, drained and rinsed
1/4 c. coconut oil
2 tsp. vanilla extract
1/2 tsp. baking powder
1/4 tsp. pink salt
6 T. chocolate chips

Topping:
1/2 c. Hershey's Special Dark cocoa powder
1/2 c. unsweetened almond milk
1 T. coconut oil
1/4 c. chopped walnuts

Directions
  1. Preheat oven to 350 degrees and line 8x8" baking pan with parchment paper.
  2. Process all brownie ingredients, except chocolate chips, in food processor until smooth.
  3. Stir in chocolate chips.
  4. Spread brownie mixture into baking pan.
  5. Bake for 30 minutes.
  6. Remove from oven and allow to cool completely.
  7. Press down on brownies using parchment paper to flatten them out.
  8. Whisk together topping ingredients, except walnuts.
  9. Spread evenly onto brownies with spatula.
  10. Top with walnuts.
  11. Refrigerate for 1 hour before slicing.

Kale Slaw

Kale Slaw

Dietary
Sugar Free
Low Carb
Calories per serving
150
Servings
4
Ingredients

4 c. chopped kale
1 c. chopped carrots
1/4 c. chopped onion
1/4 c. chopped red pepper
4 large green olives, finely chopped
2 c. coleslaw mix
2 T. nutritional yeast
2 T. avocado oil
2 T. coconut aminos
1/4 tsp. celery seed
2 T. water
1 T. apple cider vinegar
1/2 tsp. minced garlic flakes

Directions
  1. Combine kale, coleslaw mix, carrots, onion, pepper, and olives in large mixing bowl with lid.
  2. In small bowl, whisk together avocado oil, coconut aminos, water, celery seed, vinegar, garlic, and nutritional yeast.
  3. Pour dressing over slaw mix.
  4. Place lid on bowl and shake vigorously until dressing is well distributed.
  5. Refrigerate until ready to serve.

Homemade Clif Z Bars

Homemade Clif Z Bars

Dietary
Low Carb
Calories per serving
125
Servings
15
Ingredients

1 c. oat flour
1/2 c. oats
1/4 c. unsweetened cocoa powder
1 tsp. baking powder
1 tsp. baking soda
1/4 c. pea protein powder
2 T. flax meal
1/4 tsp. pink salt
1/2 c. unsweetened applesauce
1/2 c. unsweetened almond milk
2 T. date paste
1 T. peanut butter (or almond butter)
1/4 c. honey
1/4 c. + 3 T. mini chocolate chips (divided)
1 tsp. coconut oil

Directions
  1. Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
  2. Line 13x9 inch pan with parchment paper.
  3. Combine oat flour, oats, cocoa powder, baking powder, baking soda, protein powder, flax meal, and pink salt in large bowl. 
  4. In separate bowl, combine applesauce, almond milk, date paste, nut butter, and honey.
  5. Pour wet mixture into dry mixture and stir until combined.
  6. Fold in 1/4 c. chococolate chips.
  7. Spread mixture evenly into baking pan (about 1/4 inch thick), leaving about 1/4 inch border on all sides of the pan.
  8. Bake for 30 minutes. 
  9. Remove from oven and allow to cool.
  10. Slice into 15 evenly sized bars.
  11. Melt remaining 3 T. chocolate chips and coconut oil together.
  12. Transfer chocolate mixture into ziplock bag.
  13. Cut corner of ziplock bag and drizzle chocolate over bars.
  14. Place in refrigerator until chocolate hardens. 
  15. Store, in container with lid, in refrigerator.

Turkey Veggie Chili

Turkey Veggie Chili

Dietary
Sugar Free
Low Carb
Calories per serving
260
Servings
5
Ingredients

1 lb. ground turkey
1/2 eggplant, chopped
1 onion, chopped
1 green pepper, chopped
8 oz sliced mushrooms
1 (14.5 oz) can diced tomatoes
1 c. tomato sauce
1 T. Italian seasoning
1 tsp. garlic powder
2 tsp. cumin
3 T. chili powder
2 tsp. paprika
2 tsp. pink salt
1/4 tsp. cayenne pepper

Directions
  1. Cook turkey in large saucepan over medium-high heat until slightly browned.
  2. Stir in all fresh vegetables and continue to cook until beginning to soften.
  3. Stir in spices, diced tomatoes, and tomato sauce then bring to a boil.
  4. Reduce heat to simmer.
  5. Place lid on saucepan and cook for at least 15 minutes, stirring occasionally.

Chocolate Peanut Butter Bread

Chocolate Peanut Butter Bread

Dietary
Sugar Free
Low Carb
Calories per serving
175
Servings
10
Ingredients

3 ripe bananas
6 eggs
1/4 c. + 1 tsp. peanut butter
2 tsp. vanilla
2 T. unsweetened cocoa powder
1/2 tsp. pink salt
1 tsp. baking soda
1/2 c. almond flour
1/4 c. coconut flour
1 scoop whey protien powder

Directions
  1. Preheat oven to 350 degr.ees
  2. Grease 9x5 inch loaf pan.
  3. Combine bananas and eggs in blender.
  4. Pulse in peanut butter, vanilla, salt, cocoa powder, and baking soda until well incorporated.
  5. Add coconut flour, almond flour, and protein powder and blend until combined.
  6. Pour batter into loaf pan.
  7. Drizzle 1 tsp melted peanut butter on top.
  8. Bake for 60-75 minutes, until toothpick inserted in center comes out clean.
  9. Allow to cool before slicing with sharp knife.

Baked Brownie Fudge

Baked Brownie Fudge

Dietary
Low Carb
Calories per serving
40
Servings
40
Ingredients

1 1/2 c. black beans
2 eggs
1/2 c. unsweetened cocoa powder
1 scoop whey protein powder
1 c. unsweetenend applesauce
1/4 c. coconut oil
1 tsp. baking powder
1/4 tsp. pink salt
1/4 c. honey
1 tsp. vanilla extract
2 dropperfuls stevia
 

Directions
  1. Preaheat oven to 350 degrees.
  2. Grease 11x7" pan lightly.
  3. Combine beans and eggs in food processor until smooth. 
  4. Add all other ingredients and process until well combined.
  5. Transfer mixture into pan and tap on counter a few times to distribute evenly.
  6. Bake for 25 minutes.
